{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627451"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:48:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:48:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17121"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17121"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.06,0.21,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62321"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5021"},{"type":"tags","id":"5034"},{"type":"tags","id":"8433"},{"type":"tags","id":"9874"},{"type":"tags","id":"10771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman with chronic hypertension is prescribed hydralazine. Her blood pressure improves but she develops palpitations. On examination, her heart rate is 95 beats per minute.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of hydralazine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation","Reduces sympathetic outflow from the central nervous system","Blocks alpha-adrenergic receptors in the arterioles","Blocks calcium channels in cardiac myocytes","Inhibits angiotensin converting enzyme"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of hydralazine. It reduces the availability of calcium ions in vascular smooth muscle cells, leading to vasodilation primarily in arterioles rather than veins. This results in decreased peripheral vascular resistance and lowered blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces sympathetic outflow from the central nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of centrally-acting agents like clonidine, which reduce sympathetic tone by stimulating alpha-2 receptors in the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks alpha-adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of alpha blockers like prazosin, which block noradrenaline binding to alpha receptors on blood vessels, causing both arterial and venous dilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels in cardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes calcium channel blockers like verapamil, which act on L-type calcium channels in both cardiac and smooth muscle, whereas hydralazine\u0027s effect on calcium is indirect and specific to vascular smooth muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits angiotensin converting enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes ACE inhibitors like enalapril, which prevent angiotensin II formation and have additional effects on the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe selective arteriolar dilation caused by hydralazine often leads to reflex tachycardia as baroreceptors detect the drop in blood pressure. This explains the patient\u0027s increased heart rate. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydralazine causes direct vasodilation of arterioles by reducing calcium availability in vascular smooth muscle.","Hydralazine primarily affects arterioles rather than veins, leading to reduced peripheral vascular resistance.","Reflex tachycardia is a common side effect of hydralazine due to baroreceptor activation in response to arteriolar vasodilation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62321"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17121"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62321"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T13:37:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T13:37:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9811"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76819"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"